data.title: Adolf Hitler's henchmen at WWII death camps who will never be punished
data.meta_description: As 'The Bookkeeper of Auschwitz Oskar Groening is sentenced to four years for the mass murder of 300,000 Jews, Germany's top prosecutor wants many more former Nazi soldiers to face justice
data.text:
Germany's top Nazi war crimes hunter had 50 former death camp guards in his sights after an international trawl through archives and wartime service records of S.S. personnel.

While Oskar Groening was today sentenced to four years in jail for facilitating the murder of 300,000 Jews at Auschwitz, none of them are ever likely to make it into the dock.

Kurt Schrimm of Germany's Central Office for the investigation of National Socialist Crimes prepared prosecution papers against the former overseers who served at the Auschwitz extermination centre in Nazi occupied Poland during WWII.

Auschwitz, as well as being a vast prison camp where inmates worked until they died, was also the largest of the Nazi killing factories where an estimated 1.2 million people were put to death.

Scroll down for videos

Schrimm's agencies went hunting for the former guards after the successful prosecution in Germany four years ago of John Demjanjuk an ex-guard at the Sobibor camp, in Poland, where in 2011 he was convicted of an accessory to the murder of 27,900 Jews.

Demjanjuk was out on bail pending the appeal against his five year sentence when he died aged 91 of natural causes.

The case against him set a legal precedent in Germany after he was found guilty without specific crimes being levelled against him and with no eyewitnesses to report individual acts of cruelty: it was enough that he was there for him to be found guilty of crimes against humanity.

Schrimm wanted similar trials for 50 guards who they had identified as serving at Auschwitz, most of whom lived in Germany, before old age claimed them.

Schrimm works with 20 people, including five prosecutors, two police officers, clerks and interpreters, at his office in Ludwigsburg.

'We owe it to the victims and their families to bring these criminals to justice,' he said. 'Such crimes as they were involved with had never been visited upon the world before in human history.

'We are no longer sitting at desks, waiting until the cases come to us. We went hunting for these people.'

Legal loopholes, a lack of enthusiasm among prosecutors and old alliances between wartime and postwar justice officials meant that only 6,495 defendants who worked in the vast Holocaust machinery were convicted in Germany for Nazi crimes after WW2.

Local prosecutors across Germany received the files on the 50 Auschwitz guards beginning in April 2013. All were charged with conspiracy to commit murder and all were aged around 90.

Some of them lived in South America at the time - a favoured destination for Nazi war criminals who fled there after the war ended in 1945 - and authorities in Chile, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay have also been contacted to aid with extradition requests.

If Schrimm's team had been successful, the prosecutions would have been the biggest number of Nazis brought to book since trials in Germany immediately after the war.

Schrimm added: 'We are not only entitled but also morally obliged to keep track of these things. We cannot say to the victims: now so much time has passed these things no longer interest us. Justice must be served.'

But it has not been, nor will it be, served. Old age, infirmity, dementia, a lack of willingness among local prosecutors and general apathy means that all will die in their beds.

To be sure, they have traded the Hugo Boss-made S.S black uniforms patterned with the silver lightning bolts of the S.S. for elasticated trousers and tartan rugs.

The hands which once clasped riding crops and truncheons are now the texture of parchment paper, dotted with the liver spots of age.

Seven decades on from their moments in the sunshine of Hitler's regime they now appear as menacing as the kindly home helps who visit them weekly to dress and feed and give them words of comfort in the twilight of their lives.

Their pending indictments were meant to atone for decades of indifference which followed the end of WWII and the Nazi bacillus which spawned it.

With the old-guard of prosecutors linked to the Third Reich - by experience, blood ties or simply admiration for Hitler and all his works - now dead and gone, young legal guns stepped up to the bat to declare open season on the last of these enablers of mass murder.

They are people like S.S. corporal Hans Koenig, 94, an ethnic German from Bratislava in what was Czechoslovakia who now lives in a small town near Stuttgart.

Known as a 'bruiser' in Auschwitz, a guard who allegedly liked cruelty for its own sake, he doesn't deny being at the human abbatoir. 'At the time the German ethnic group I belonged to had to be tested and I was happy to be a part of that,' he said.

He claims no knowledge of the gas chambers, of the 'selection' of victims on the infamous train platform at the camp in occupied Poland, of starvations, beatings, murder. 'They should leave me alone,' he moans. 'It was all a long time ago.'

And he is to be left alone: no further action was ordered after he was judged unfit to stand trial.

Most claimed failing memories to keep them out of the dock. Stefan M, 89, was a member of the Death's Head battalion of the S.S. guarding the inmates at Auschwitz.

He took part in executions of prisoners by firing squads, say prosecutors, and on October 8 1942 fired with five other S.S. men at ten inmates attempting to escape. All unarmed victims perished.

Stefan M, who lives outside the gracious Bavarian town of Bamberg, tells journalists who call: 'I am sorry, but my husband is suffering badly from dementia. He cannot remember the war year at all.'

Result: case closed.

That is the bleat also of Gertru Elli Schmid, now 92. A little old lady in Hamburg, she was formerly an S.S. guard at Majdanek in the Polish city of Lublin where an estimated 235,000 people were murdered during WWII.

Prosecutors have traced her S.S. identity card bearing the number 312 which bears the words: 'The holder is authorised to carry arms.' After service in Majdanek she was sent to Auschwitz.

Now wheelchair bound, she was tracked down by the popular daily newspaper Bild. Her daughter, pushing her in a wheelchair, told the newspaper: 'We know that my mother had something to do with Auschwitz.

'We have tried to talk with her about it but her memory doesn't really function any more.'

Hans Lipschis is a former member of the Waffen-SS who worked at Auschwitz.

In May 2013, at the age of 93, Lipschis was arrested for being complicit in murder.

He claims that although he worked at Auschwitz, he was only a cook. He was found to be unfit for trial in December 2013 and March 2014.

Meanwhile top of the Nazi most wanted list according to the Simon Wiesenthal Centre is 93-year-old Gerhard Sommer, who was found unfit to be tried in May because of his 'severe dementia'.

The former S.S. lieutenant is thought to have played a major role in the mass murder of 560 civilians in the Italian village of Sant-Anna di Stazzema in 1944.

If he did stand trial, prosecutors believed there was a serious chance of him being 'charged with 342 cases of murder, committed cruelly and on base motives'.

Second most wanted on that list was Vladimir Katriuk, who died aged 93 in Canada this year.

Russia accused him of taking part in the 1943 massacre in Khatyn, which was then in the Soviet Union, and demanded that he be deported to Moscow to face trial.

Katriuk denied any involvement in the massacre of 156 villagers who were killed by a Nazi battalion.

But eyewitnesses claim he lay outside a barn which had been set on fire with people inside - and he shot anyone who tried to escape.

Soren Kam from Denmark volunteered as an officer in the Schalburg Corps - a 'Viking' division of the S.S. - and was one of three men who killed a Danish anti-Nazi newspaper editor.

He escaped to Germany where he gained citizenship in 1956 and his adopted country refused to extradite him to Denmark where he was convicted of the murder in-absentia. He died aged 93 in March - receiving no punishment for his crime.

In April, former S.S. sergeant Johann Robert Riss, 88, was guilty in-absentia at a military trial in Rome for his part in the massacre of 184 innocent people including women and children in the village of Padule di Fucecchio in Tuscany.

In one of the worst Nazi atrocities, survivors told how villagers were shot by German machine gunners and of a two-year-old toddler, crying in the arms of its dead mother, being killed with a blow from a rifle butt.

The military court found that the three accused – Ernst Pistor, 91, an ex-Wehrmacht captain; Fritz Jauss, 94, a former warrant officer; and Riss – took an active part in the brutal massacre on Aug 23, 1944.

Riss, now 88, has not been heard off since January 2011, and adds to the long list of Nazi killers who escaped justice.

Another is former Lithuanian Security Police (Saugumas) official Algimantas Dailide, 94, who was convicted of arresting 12 Jews who tried to flee from the Vilna Ghetto.

After the war Dailide fled to the United States where he sought refuge and invented a back story where he said he had been a forester.

There, he became a real estate agent in Gulfport, Florida, until 1997 when his citizenship was revoked in 1997. He left the United States on his own in 2004.

In 2006 - when he was 86 - a Lithuanian court found him guilty - but he was not sentenced to prison 'because he is very old and does not pose danger to society'.

Helmut Oberlander was facing deportation from Canada in January this year over his links to a Nazi killing unit, the Toronto Star reported.

He maintains he only served as a translator for the infamous EK10A unit, which carried out the mass executions of Jews and other civilians - and claims he never participated in any killings.

Ivan Kalimon, who served from 1941 to 1944 as a volunteer, Freiwilliger, in the Ukrainian Auxiliary Police, whose members were actively engaged in the persecution and extermination of Jews in Lvov that has later become Lemberg.

During the Second World War, Kalimon was involved in the sweeps held in a Lvov ghetto, deportation of Jews and mass executions.

At the very least, there is one documented murder committed by Kalimon, who was number seven on the list of the most wanted Nazi war criminals.

He moved to the US in 1949 where he lived in Michigan. He was fighting extradition from the US to face justice when he died last year.

Ladislaus Csatary was the Royal Hungarian Police assistant commander in Kassa, Hungary, in 1944.

Csatary was accused of organising the deportation of 15,700 Jews to Auschwitz.

He was convicted in absentia for war crimes in Czechoslovakia in 1948 and sentenced to death.

But he escaped to Canada in 1949 claiming to be a Yugoslav national and settled in Montreal where he became an art dealer and became a citizen in 1955.

In 1997, his Canadian citizenship was revoked by the federal Cabinet for not giving enough information on his citizenship application.

He left the country two months later but was never charged with war crimes in Canada.

In 2012, Csatáry was found living in Budapest, Hungary, and in July of that year he was arrested and taken into custody for questioning by the Hungarian authorities for questioning.

In the same month Slovak Justice Minister Tomáš Borec announced he was ready to prosecute Csatáry and asked Hungary to extradite him.

But Csatáry died on August 10, 2013 from pneumonia at a hospital in Budapest aged 98, before he could be brought to trial.

In June a German court said it would not proceed with the trial of former SS sergeant Hubert Z who served as a medic at Auschwitz because the 94-year-old is suffering from dementia.

The Neubrandenburg state court said that experts had determined that Hubert Z. was unfit for trial and that his condition was worsening.

Now 93 and living in Mecklenburg, Germany, he was charged with 3,681 counts of accessory to murder during his time at the death camp in Poland.

Hubert's son told reporters: 'My father is an old man, he has lived his life, leave him in peace.'

Aribert Heim, an Austrian SS doctor known as Dr Death, was never brought to justice.

He has been accused of killing hundreds of inmates at the Mauthausen concentration camp in Austria.

One survivor said Dr Death castrated, dissected a kidney and removed the second, then decapitated a young prisoner who had come in with a swollen foot. The head was boiled to removed the flesh so it could be used as a paperweight.

Just 27 years old at the time, he murdered hundreds of inmates by injecting them with various liquids including petrol, phenol, water and poison, all in the interests of seeing which killed them the fastest.

Organs were removed from conscious patients, and in one case he removed the tattooed flesh of a prisoner to make seat coverings for the camp commandant's flat.

Justice evaded him at war's end, but the past did catch up with him eventually. In the 1960s he was forced to flee Germany as prosecutors finally pieced together his crimes.

A court sentenced him in absentia in 1979 and he was on the run until his death in Egypt in 1992.

Alois Brunner, the right-hand man of leading Holocaust architect Adolf Eichmann, sent European Jews to the gas chambers.

During the Second World War, Brunner sent 47,000 Jews in Austria, 44,000 in Greece, 23,500 in France and 14,000 in Slovakia to camps where most were murdered.

Brunner escaped to Syria in the early 1950s, where he is said to have lived and worked using the name Dr. Georg Fischer.

Brunner was tried and sentenced to death in absentia in France in 1954, but as the Syrian government refused to acknowledge that Brunner resided in the country, he was never extradited.

He is believed to have been working for President Hafez al-Assad, the father of current president Bashar al-Assad, as a government adviser on torture, security and terrorism.

Several attempts were made on his life by Israeli intelligence, and he lost several fingers and an eye in two separate letter bombings organised by Mossad in the 60s and early 80s.

It is believed he died in Syria in 2010.

In an interview with a German magazine in 1985, he reportedly said: 'My only regret is I didn't murder more Jews'.

In 2012, the Australian high court ruled that Charles Zentai could not be extradited to Hungary to face accusations he tortured and killed a Jewish teenager during World War II.

He denies allegations that he was involved in the fatal beating of Peter Balazs for not wearing the Star of David to identify him as Jewish.

German-born Erna Wallisch, alleged to have murdered prisoners in a Nazi concentration camp during World War Two, died in 2008 at the age of 86.

She passed away a month after Austria, prompted by new testimony from Poland, reopened an investigation into her past that had been dropped in 1973 for lack of hard evidence.

The Polish findings, based on witness statements, suggested Wallisch may have committed murder in the Majdanek camp near Lublin in Nazi-occupied Poland. Wallisch always said she had only guarded prisoners.

Klaas Carel Faber, a Nazi war criminal who escaped from a Dutch jail and lived as a fugitive in Germany for 60 years died at the age of 90 in 2012.

Faber was sentenced to death in 1947 in the Netherlands for killing at least 11 people at a staging post for Dutch Jews being taken to concentration camps.

His sentence was commuted to life imprisonment but he escaped in 1952 and fled to Germany, where he became a citizen and had lived since 1961 in the Bavarian town of Ingolstadt.

He had long resisted attempts by his native Netherlands to extradite him and died shortly before prosecutors in Ingolstadt were preparing to detain him.

Early last year gigantic posters went up in Germany. They were of the iconic, horrifying gates of Auschwitz with the railway lines that brought the doomed passing through its gate en-route to the infamous selection ramp.

'Late, but not too late' was the message on the posters designed by the Wiesenthal centre. The posters contained a phone number asking Germans to ring in with confidential information if they knew the whereabouts of a suspected war criminal.

Some of the latest suspects came on the radar because of this campaign, among them Professor Johannes Adam, now 90 and honoured by one university as 'the foremost medical statistician of former East Germany.'

But in his youth he was a Section Leader in the S.S. at Auschwitz.

He has never spoken a word about his past. And he has a nimble mind to this day so would be unable to claim to be suffering from dementia if he is ever indicted.

Another Nazi war criminal identified through the campaign is Gisela S, 90, who now lives in an OAP home in northern Germany. She was also employed at Auschwitz.

And Charlotte S, 94, a guard at the women's concentration camp of Ravensbrueck where Jewish diarist Anne Frank was briefly incarcerated before being sent to Belsen, where she died, was also fearing retribution at the final moments of her life.

Ravensbrueck was a notoriously brutal camp and Charlotte S. a feared woman who beat prisoners and unleashed her Alsatian dog on them.

Tried in Communist East Germany after the war, she was sentenced to 15 months' imprisonment for assaults on prisoners and stealing their possessions, but more recently prosecutors hoped to charge her with accessory to murder. But she too has been told she won't be prosecuted due to her age.

'Unfortunately, very few people who committed the crimes has to pay for them,' said Efraim Zuroff, the Wiesenthal centre's top Nazi hunter. 'The passage of time in no way diminishes the crimes.'

The cases were sent to the responsible state prosecutors' offices in 11 of Germany's 16 states.
